Jenkins follows a master–agent (controller–node) architecture where the Jenkins controller manages tasks, plugins, and configurations, while agents (nodes) execute builds and tests across distributed environments. This design enables scalability, flexibility, and efficient CI/CD pipelines.

---

Controller
Central server that hosts the Jenkins UI and core services.

AGENTS
Remote or local machines that perform build/test tasks.

Jobs
Defined tasks (build, test, deploy) configured via UI or Jenkinsfile.

Plugins
Extend Jenkins functionality (SCM integration, Docker, Kubernetes, etc.).

Pipelines
Declarative or scripted workflows defined in code (Jenkinsfile).

-----------------------------------------------------CI → Continuous Integration: Developers frequently merge code into a shared repo, and every change is automatically built and tested.

CD → Continuous Delivery: Ensures that code passing CI is always in a deployable state, ready for release at any time.

## CDN → Continuous Deployment: Goes one step further — every validated change is automatically released to production without manual approval.

